column18: What is your annual household income?
column19: What was your overall impression of this event (quality, lighting, sound, value)?
column20: Please share any other suggestions or ideas that would help us enhance your experience at Gesa Power House Theatre. If you would like someone to respond to your feedback, please include your contact information. Thank you!

column19: All were great!  No complaints or suggestions.   And thank you for the two trailers before the film--now I want to see both of those films!
Hard to hear questions and comments that were made after the show. Having a wireless microphone would be a good idea.
column20:
Overall we love the theater and the shows that are brought to our community. 
Thank you!

column19: Excellent film; excellent discussion led by Warren Etheredge.

The movie was very interesting, with nice scenery, good portrayals of her fantasies and observations of interesting workplace interactions, and suspenseful romance.  Her discomfort with social interactions was understandable to me because I also have been uncomfortable in groups.
I enjoyed the film and the hosted discussion after the film.
Good film, but a bit hard to hear some of the actors. Would have liked subtitles or a bit more volume

The volume was far too low, at least for the first portion of the film. I was sitting on the right side of the theatre, and from what I could tell it seemed like the sound was only coming out of the speakers on the right side.

Fantastic choice of film to show at the Powerhouse Theatre--a good value indeed.  Quality films like this will entice me to return for more.  Sound was clear.  Lighting was good. Was delighted to see Warren Etheredge made the trip over from Seattle to be at the screening in person.  That certainly indicates how important this film is.  Thanks to him!
column20: Wasn't sure what to expect based on the title.  The pre-film video clip gave me some helpful insight that it might not be entirely depressing.  Was initially thinking it may focus on suicide; then again, it could just be a coming of "old" age story and facing death.  The unravelling of the story kept me intrigued, and the primary relationship was brutally honest.  Found it quirky and sincere.  People seemed familiar with Daisy Ridley.  Haven't seen all the Star Wars films that brought her fame.  Glad local actor, Rich Hintz, was featured.

column19: Sound had one minor blip but the screen was a good size and the picture was crisp. Seats at good angle.
column20: All the good parts were shown in the trailer. This show was slow and awkward. At the end I just wanted to use the restroom and go home so the post show Q&A was not my favorite.
